1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,922
One of the biggest names in America’s music industry – Quincy Jones – has died at the age of 91.

2
00:00:09,922 --> 00:00:23,409
A family statement said Jones passed away Sunday night surrounded by family members at his home in the Bel Air neighborhood of Los Angeles.

3
00:00:23,409 --> 00:00:36,741
Jones is known for working with many top names in the music industry, including superstars Michael Jackson, Frank Sinatra and Ray Charles.

4
00:00:36,741 --> 00:00:44,517
Throughout his 65-year career, he worked with hundreds of other music artists.

5
00:00:44,517 --> 00:01:00,576
Jones’ publicist Arnold Robinson said in a statement, “Tonight, with full but broken hearts, we must share the news of our father and brother Quincy Jones’ passing.”

6
00:01:00,576 --> 00:01:15,375
It added, “And although this is an incredible loss for our family, we celebrate the great life that he lived and know there will never be another like him.”

7
00:01:15,375 --> 00:01:27,623
Born in Chicago in 1933, Jones said an early music influence was the hymns his mother used to sing around the house.

8
00:01:27,623 --> 00:01:34,680
Early on, he played music, the trumpet, and led others in band music.

9
00:01:34,680 --> 00:01:41,668
As a very young man, Jones used to run with gangs on the South Side of Chicago.

10
00:01:41,668 --> 00:01:50,790
But he later rose to the top of show business, becoming one of the first Black business leaders in Hollywood.

11
00:01:50,790 --> 00:01:57,693
Later, he established himself as a major composer and producer.

12
00:01:57,693 --> 00:02:09,486
Jones shaped recordings by jazz greats such as Miles Davis and produced hits for Sinatra and Ella Fitzgerald.

13
00:02:09,486 --> 00:02:20,423
And he helped organize the 1985 money-raising event for Africa that resulted in the song We Are the World.

14
00:02:20,423 --> 00:02:26,048
The song went on to become one of the biggest hits of its time.

15
00:02:26,048 --> 00:02:32,116
Jones composed music for Roots and In the Heat of the Night.

16
00:02:32,116 --> 00:02:40,502
He also organized President Bill Clinton's first inaugural celebration in 1993.

17
00:02:40,502 --> 00:02:48,311
Jones also wrote several movie scores and co-produced the film The Color Purple.

18
00:02:48,311 --> 00:03:01,791
In addition, he co-produced the highly successful 1990s television show The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air, which launched the career of Will Smith.

19
00:03:01,791 --> 00:03:11,096
Jones’s work with superstar Michael Jackson still represents one of his most lasting successes.

20
00:03:11,096 --> 00:03:25,537
He and Jackson made three wildly popular albums: Off the Wall in 1979, Thriller in 1982, and Bad in 1987.

21
00:03:25,537 --> 00:03:32,316
Thriller sold more than 20 million copies in 1983 alone.

22
00:03:32,316 --> 00:03:44,039
It helped Jackson become the first major Black artist to have a video played on MTV and influenced countless other performers.

23
00:03:44,039 --> 00:03:53,956
Jones later explained, “Michael had the look and the voice, and I had every sound you can think of.”

24
00:03:53,956 --> 00:04:06,399
Jones was known for keeping company with presidents and foreign leaders, movie stars and musicians, philanthropists and business leaders.

25
00:04:06,399 --> 00:04:21,217
His circle of friends included some of the most famous people of the 20th century, including artist Pablo Picasso, Pope John Paul II and Nelson Mandela.

26
00:04:21,217 --> 00:04:31,939
The list of Jones’ honors and awards fills 18 pages in his 2001 autobiography Q.

27
00:04:31,939 --> 00:04:35,378
The book made him a best-selling writer.

28
00:04:35,378 --> 00:04:47,744
He won a total of 27 Grammy Awards, as well as two honorary Academy Awards and an Emmy for the television series Roots.

29
00:04:47,744 --> 00:05:04,710
Jones also received France's Legion d'Honneur, the Rudolph Valentino Award from the Republic of Italy and a Kennedy Center honor for his influence over American culture.

30
00:05:04,710 --> 00:05:21,577
He was the subject of a 1990 documentary called "Listen Up: The Lives of Quincy Jones," as well as the 2018 film Quincy, directed by his daughter, Rashida Jones.

31
00:05:21,577 --> 00:05:24,336
I’m Bryan Lynn.